==English==

===Etymology===

Perhaps a calque of the Latin phrase [[potiusque sero quam nunquam]] from the 4th book<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/txt/ah/Livy/Livy04.html |title=Livy's History of Rome |accessdate=May 29, 2007 |author=Butterfield, Bruce J. |date=1996 |format=HTML | publisher=Marquette University ([http://mu.edu mu.edu]) |language=English.}}</ref> of ''[[w:Ab Urbe condita (book)|Ab Urbe condita]]'' (''History of Rome'') by [[w:Livy|Titus Livius]], around 27 BC.

===Adverb===
{{head|en|adverb|head=[[better]] [[late]] than [[never]]}}

# It's better to do something late, than to never do it at all.
#* '''1996.''' Titus Livius (translation). ''Livy's History of Rome'' (in English):
#*: ''Their insolence and recklessness must be opposed, and '''better late than never'''.''

